Sure! Here's a JavaScript function that generates a random pun using the words "student" and "test" from an array of puns:

```javascript
function getRandomPun() {
    const puns = [
        "Why did the student study for the test in the sauna? He wanted a higher degree.",
        "Why was the math book sad? Because it had too many problems.",
        "Why did the teacher wear sunglasses? Because his class was so bright.",
        "Why did the student fail his history test? He thought World War II was fought between Facebook and Twitter.",
        "Why did the student bring a ladder to the test? He heard the questions were on another level.",
        "What's a student's favorite type of music during a test? Classical, because it has all the right notes.",
        "Why did the student bring a pencil to the test? It was the 'write' thing to do."
    ];

    const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * puns.length);
    return puns[randomIndex];
}

// Example usage:
console.log(getRandomPun());
```

This function selects a random pun from the `puns` array and returns it. You can call `getRandomPun()` to get a random pun each time.
